WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:20.340
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Hello.

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:22.070
My name is Stephen Winick, and I'm
here at the Library of Congress

00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:23.370
with the band BeauSoleil,

00:00:23.370 --> 00:00:26.220
or the BeauSoleil Quartet,
as they're called today.

00:00:26.220 --> 00:00:29.330
And I'm interviewing them for
the American Folklife Center here

00:00:29.330 --> 00:00:30.990
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:34.730
So, I'm going to sort of
address some general questions

00:00:34.730 --> 00:00:36.530
to all of you.

00:00:36.530 --> 00:00:40.760
In particular, a question about
what the Cajun music scene was

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:42.480
like when you were growing up.

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:45.630
So to sort of set the scene
for how Cajun music has changed

00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:48.620
over the last 30 years or 40 years.

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:49.920
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Keep going.

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:52.810
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Fifty years.

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:55.760
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well, I
don't think it was ever a scene.

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:00.000
You know, the music was created for
the community, just for the people

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.860
in Southwest Louisiana, as a way
of communicating news, and I mean,

00:01:04.860 --> 00:01:08.130
it's very, Louisiana,
it's a beautiful state,

00:01:08.130 --> 00:01:09.890
but it's very hard,
and you work hard.

00:01:09.890 --> 00:01:11.360
But you play hard too.

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:15.050
So the music was very
much a part of that.

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:22.230
My father had five sisters, and
you know, two of them sang ballads.

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:25.970
And then we would have
these parties, you know,

00:01:25.970 --> 00:01:28.600
family get togethers where
there was a meal or whatever

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:30.730
where everybody would show up and
everybody would play something.

00:01:30.730 --> 00:01:32.690
It didn't matter what,
whether it was a violin

00:01:32.690 --> 00:01:35.580
or a trumpet or piano, whatever.

00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:39.880
And I think everybody
just really liked the fact

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:41.880
that it was still sung in French.

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:44.670
The old people liked it because
it was called old people's music.

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:47.190
We never called this
Cajun music growing up.

00:01:47.190 --> 00:01:50.450
And, it was French music, or la
musique Francaise [phonetic].

00:01:50.450 --> 00:01:54.690
And it was just something,
you know, me personally,

00:01:54.690 --> 00:01:56.800
just kind of took for granted.

00:01:56.800 --> 00:01:58.780 position:56%
It was like, you know, somebody said

00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:00.370
when did you learn
your first Cajun song?

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:03.010
I said, when did you learn your
first Christmas song, you know.

00:02:03.010 --> 00:02:05.040
It was kind of the same thing.

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:10.900
But everybody did it, and I'm
talking about the 50s now, 1950s.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:16.390
And there was 22 civil
parishes in Southwest Louisiana,

00:02:16.390 --> 00:02:18.960
it's like a triangle,
that speak French.

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.400
And all those different
parishes had different songs

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.000
and different people.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.930
A lot had been forgotten because
the original recordings, you know,

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:31.010
with the RCA victor coming in,
they wanted to sell Victrolas,

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:32.870
so they were recorded
for commercial use.

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:35.760
That was from like '28 to '36.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.780
And then World War II happened.

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:41.150
A lot of people, you know, realized
what they had when they went away.

00:02:41.150 --> 00:02:44.550
Because we were so, it was
different, like no other place,

00:02:44.550 --> 00:02:46.890
obviously, speaking French.

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:50.540
And so I think there was a
resurgence, always a resurgence

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:53.050
that happened then
in the 50s, the 60s,

00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:56.300
and then of course,
it was television.

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:59.180
And when we had our first
local station in Lafayette.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:00.480
It was KLFY TV.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:05.210
And every Sunday morning they
had [inaudible], which was a show

00:03:05.210 --> 00:03:06.860
that Aldus Roger played on.

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:08.690
It was like this big band.

00:03:08.690 --> 00:03:10.090
I mean we used to hear
like an accordion

00:03:10.090 --> 00:03:11.520
and fiddle player or somebody.

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:15.620
There was like twin fiddlers, steel
guitar, electric guitar, drums,

00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:16.920
you know, bass and the whole bit.

00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:20.510
So that was like another
resurgence I think.

00:03:20.510 --> 00:03:24.480
But I think music has
always been in our culture.

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:29.590
So that wasn't, you know, that
was something that was just there.

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:32.360
What happened sort of in the
30s, people were punished

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:35.250
for speaking French
on the school grounds.

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:37.620
So either they left school.

00:03:37.620 --> 00:03:38.950
You know that joke, right.

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:41.220
You know, when they went to
math class they said say one.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.260
One. They say, say
two, they said bye.

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:47.920
So, but it like happened,
it's not really a joke.

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:49.220
It happened.

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:50.520
But a lot of people preserved it.

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:52.210
And in Southwest Louisiana
growing up,

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:55.340
a lot of people didn't
speak English in the pier

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:58.630
because they didn't have to.

00:03:58.630 --> 00:04:00.500
And so that was that.

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:08.780
Now, what happened to us, for me,
is that when someone died that was,

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:11.880 position:56%
you know, a proponent of this music,
you know, not only did you grieve

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:15.130
for the death, physically death,
but whatever history they had

00:04:15.130 --> 00:04:16.710
because our history was basic oral.

00:04:16.710 --> 00:04:20.510
With the music too, but our
history of our culture too.

00:04:20.510 --> 00:04:25.710
So for us, I mean, it's like
we didn't want to see that.

00:04:25.710 --> 00:04:27.640
So we decided, well we have
to do something about it.

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:29.230
How do you do something about it?

00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:30.900
You learn the music.

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:32.200
And just like that.

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:34.530
I mean it's not for no
reward or no end result,

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:38.850
the thing was just
it needed to be done.

00:04:38.850 --> 00:04:40.150
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
So you got a sense

00:04:40.150 --> 00:04:42.470
that the older generation
was passing away

00:04:42.470 --> 00:04:44.400
and you decided it was
time to [inaudible] yeah.

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:47.930
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Because nobody
was looking at it as it should be,

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:50.890
as we thought it should be, because
it's not just two-step and waltzes.

00:04:50.890 --> 00:04:53.240
I mean there's a lot of
information in there.

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:56.060
There's a lot of cultural
information.

00:04:56.060 --> 00:04:57.360
And we thought we were isolated.

00:04:57.360 --> 00:04:59.940
We though nobody in the
world knew about this stuff.

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:02.840
And that started to change
a lot in the 60s too,

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:05.980
when some groups went
to Newport, etcetera.

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:08.180
It happened to us when we
were invited to go to France.

00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:09.990
But anyway, I don't want to
be long-winded about this.

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:14.050
But it was something that I
just want to say that the people

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:17.740
who held the music did
it because they had to.

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:19.040
I mean, it was just a passion.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:21.900
It was a remarkable passion,
not because of any kind

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.860
of reward except the fact
that they knew these songs.

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:27.230
And people, like fiddle
players, like [inaudible].

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:30.590
I mean he would sing song
about kings and queens,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:33.180
and we knew he never
knew any kings or queens

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:34.480
or even knew what that was.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:38.130
But the fact the music keeps
on going, regenerating.

00:05:38.130 --> 00:05:40.530
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So you mention
that early period when, you know,

00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:44.230
in the 20s and 30s when there
were commercial music made

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:45.530
of Cajun music.

00:05:45.530 --> 00:05:48.980
Were those still influential on
people when you were growing up?

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:51.500
I mean, were they still
listening to those records, or?

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:54.490
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well, you
don't have those machines, 78s.

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:58.110
What happened, a lot
of, this is one example.

00:05:58.110 --> 00:06:00.250
This is like, I mentioned
Amede Ardoin,

00:06:00.250 --> 00:06:04.480
who was the first creole really
accordion player and real prolific.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:06.640
And we play about 80% of his songs.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:10.570
I mean Cajun repertoire,
well creole repertoire now.

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:14.670
There was a blind, almost
blind Cajun guy, white guy,

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:16.750
who learned all his songs.

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:19.610
And most people thought, this
guy has really earned his name,

00:06:19.610 --> 00:06:20.910
came up with all these songs.

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:23.560
And nobody could reference
back to the 78s.

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:30.220
The first time I really listened
to a 78 was on a 33 1/3 LP

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:32.590
from Chris Strachwitz,
Arhoolie Records.

00:06:32.590 --> 00:06:36.700
We did this, a five series
that we just went crazy.

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:39.910
Because we thought, oh
this is a long time ago.

00:06:39.910 --> 00:06:41.300
It's ancient history.

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:43.520
And then when I first met Dennis,
the first time I met Dennis,

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:45.190
I said I thought you were dead.

00:06:45.190 --> 00:06:46.830
He said not yet.

00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:49.610
So that's a big jump too.

00:06:49.610 --> 00:06:52.040
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: And I mean, you
also mentioned that sort of moment

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:56.180
in the 60s when groups started
going to places like Newport.

00:06:56.180 --> 00:06:57.590
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet:
But they were not,

00:06:57.590 --> 00:06:59.210
I mean at home they
didn't believe it.

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:00.510
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:07:00.510 --> 00:07:01.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: You know,
it wasn't like they were going

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:03.110
to make a living about
this, you know.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:04.860
It was just, it was regular people.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:08.210
You know, people, nobody
really made a living at this.

00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:10.310
I mean you played Saturday
nights or whatever.

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:13.470
I mean we had a lot of people
came from there like Vin Bruce

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:15.860
and Jimmy C. Newman
who went to Nashville.

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:18.200
Doug and Rusty Kershaw, etcetera.

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:19.500
But you had to get out.

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:20.800
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right, right.

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:22.100
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Of Louisiana.

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:23.400
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah.

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:26.430 position:56%
Well tell me about some of the guys
that you sought out and worked with.

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:28.670
You know, start with Dennis
since you already mentioned him.

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:29.970
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well
Dennis, like I said,

00:07:29.970 --> 00:07:31.270
I first met him I thought
the was dead.

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:32.570
You know, it was a joke.

00:07:32.570 --> 00:07:33.870
And he says, no.

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:35.810
So I went to study with
him where I had a grant

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:38.180
for the National Endowment.

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:39.990
And with his brother-in-law
Sidney Corville [phonetic].

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:44.880
Because, to me, that was the
oldest form of Cajun music,

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:46.200
what we call French music.

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:49.670
And it was so, the
twin fiddles styles.

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:54.550
Which was not popular and
not played by anybody else.

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:57.760
This recorded in the
20s, or late 20s and 30s,

00:07:57.760 --> 00:07:59.060
so this style was not there.

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:01.960
A lot of modern musicians
would always say,

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:04.370
why are you wasting your
time learning that music.

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:05.670
I said, are you kidding?

00:08:05.670 --> 00:08:06.970
This is the essence.

00:08:06.970 --> 00:08:10.800
But it wasn't the popular country
and westernized Cajun music.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:12.210
It was dance hall at that time.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:15.710
I was very much interested
in the blues in this music,

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:19.800
and there was two bluesy
creole musicians.

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:23.060
One was Canray Fontenot, and
the other was Bebe Carriere.

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:25.960
Because they had a certain
style that you didn't,

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:27.340 position:56%
there was always blues in our music.

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:29.600
I was always interested,
where did this come from?

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:30.900
You know, in Louisiana.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:32.750
Because Louisiana blues
is different.

00:08:32.750 --> 00:08:38.170 position:56%
I mean there are 12 bar, 16 bar, you
know from the Delta in Louisiana.

00:08:38.170 --> 00:08:41.780
But these Cajun French
blues is a little different.

00:08:41.780 --> 00:08:45.990 position:56%
And I guess the, and of course, the
Balfa brothers, both Will and Dewey,

00:08:45.990 --> 00:08:48.890
you know, they were very influent,

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:51.400
because that totally,
we love their music.

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:53.760
Because there was acoustic,
when it was away from Louisiana,

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:55.200
[inaudible] Louisiana
it was electric.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:56.500
But nevertheless.

00:08:56.500 --> 00:09:00.110
And another man that I found,
he name was Varise Conner.

00:09:00.110 --> 00:09:01.630
And I said Conner, what is that?

00:09:01.630 --> 00:09:02.930
It's Britain.

00:09:02.930 --> 00:09:05.720
He says oh no, my grandfather
was an O'Conner.

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:07.050
So, O'Conner.

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:10.900
And he played a certain style
very lilting fiddle style

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:12.950
that he had never played
with an accordion.

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:16.200
So it was kind of, you know,
because when you play a fiddle

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:20.390
and accordion, people like
Hector Duhon, he was another guy.

00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:24.690
And he played a certain sickening
style that was pretty amazing.

00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:27.920
But he, the accordion that was the
main instrument because it was loud

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:29.590
and etcetera and a lot
of things like that.

00:09:29.590 --> 00:09:31.460
So those are the people basically.

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:34.570
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So Mitch,
why don't you mention Dewey,

00:09:34.570 --> 00:09:36.050
because I know you
worked with Dewey as well.

00:09:36.050 --> 00:09:38.240
So what was that like?

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:41.600
How did you meet him, and how
did you start to play with him?

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:43.860
&gt;&gt; Mitchell Reed: I used
to go to Marc Savoy's Jam

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:45.900
when I was learning,
when I was a kid.

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:48.160 position:56%
And I played string bass over there,

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:53.310
and one time when Mac Savoy was
like, hey Mitchell, come over here.

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:54.800
Dewey's on the phone.

00:09:54.800 --> 00:09:56.100
I was like what?

00:09:56.100 --> 00:09:57.400
Dewey Balfa?

00:09:57.400 --> 00:09:58.700
Yes. He needs a bass player.

00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:01.390
His bass player got in a
wreck the night before.

00:10:01.390 --> 00:10:02.690
&gt;&gt; That's terrible.

00:10:02.690 --> 00:10:06.820 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mitchell Reed: And I had a gig
at the Liberty just all of a sudden.

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:09.150
And so Marc hands me
the phone, he was like,

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:11.040
alright, do you know Cajun music?

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:12.340
I said yeah.

00:10:12.340 --> 00:10:13.970
He said you know the chords?

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:15.270
I said yeah.

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:17.810 position:56%
He said okay, don't mess up tonight.

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:19.610
I'm going to trust you.

00:10:19.610 --> 00:10:24.730
So I got to the Liberty, and my
family's all from Mamou, and Dewey,

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:26.660
the Balfas are all from Mamou.

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:29.660
And so when he found
out who my family was,

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:33.590
then I became part of
the family, you know.

00:10:33.590 --> 00:10:34.890
And it was awesome.

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:40.250
And then we came here in '98
and played for two weeks.

00:10:40.250 --> 00:10:41.880
And it was like Jamie Berzas.

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:46.270
There was a guy, Dudley
Abair [phonetic] maybe,

00:10:46.270 --> 00:10:47.970
I think, that played guitar.

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:51.120
But we played with
the Lawtell Playboys.

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:53.490
And Dewey was awesome.

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:58.250
I never took fiddle lessons
because my hero was Dennis McGee,

00:10:58.250 --> 00:11:02.270
and I never could really pick up
the way Dewey wanted me to play.

00:11:02.270 --> 00:11:05.110
He was a really strict teacher
like when he'd teach you,

00:11:05.110 --> 00:11:06.870
you have to learn the chords first.

00:11:06.870 --> 00:11:08.740
And it was that Balfa style.

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:12.690
And I was learning more
the melodies from Dennis.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:16.250
So he'd get fed up and
say okay, go practice.

00:11:16.250 --> 00:11:18.510
So I was mainly his bass player.

00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:23.780
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Well you
had talked about the difference

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:27.360
between Cajun fiddle and
other regional fiddle styles.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:29.110
I mean it's quite different.

00:11:29.110 --> 00:11:30.410
And I think people can hear it

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:34.210
but maybe not understand
what they're hearing.

00:11:35.350 --> 00:11:37.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mitchell Reed: Yeah, it's a lot
of different styles, like Mike said,

00:11:37.830 --> 00:11:41.260
creole like you have
Canray and Bois Sec.

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:44.940
And they played creole
and the Cartier family.

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:48.140
They played the same tunes that
the white players were playing,

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:52.590
but it just had that, it had that
kind of different groove to it.

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:54.960
And I always like creole.

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:56.260
That was kind of my thing.

00:11:56.260 --> 00:11:59.820
And to me, Dennis McGee, although
he was a white, Irish guy,

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:01.760
he played more of that creole style

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:05.660
because he'd play with
Amede, you know.

00:12:05.660 --> 00:12:06.960
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:09.910
Well, I mean, just the purposes of
people who might be watching this,

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:11.380
of course, we use that word creole,

00:12:11.380 --> 00:12:13.540
and it means so many
different things.

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:14.840
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Yes.

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:16.420
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So in this
context, explain what we're talking

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:17.720
about when we say creole.

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:19.020
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well Creole is

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:22.800
like rural French-speaking
people of color.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:24.830
I mean that's the easiest
way to do it.

00:12:24.830 --> 00:12:28.390
And, because there were a
lot of free people of color,

00:12:28.390 --> 00:12:30.710
even though they were black,
in Southwest Louisiana.

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:32.010
And they were side-by-side

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:34.750
with whoever was there,
but mostly French.

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:37.300
Not only Cajun, but
they were French too.

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:39.800
But they learned, there
was American songs.

00:12:39.800 --> 00:12:43.660
I mean, there was a lot of, you
know, in the Library of Congress

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:46.730
when Alan Lomax went down,
and he recorded Wayne Perry.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:48.770
Anyplace like [inaudible] hen.

00:12:48.770 --> 00:12:50.070
What other songs?

00:12:50.070 --> 00:12:51.370
And Sittin' on Top of the World.

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:52.850
But it doesn't sound
like that at all.

00:12:52.850 --> 00:12:56.720
So it's, you know, wherever it
comes from, whether it's Appalachia

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:01.670
or whatever, the music is a
reflection of the landscape.

00:13:01.670 --> 00:13:05.400
And Louisiana, it's
definitely, it's muggy, it's hot,

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:08.300
it's muddy and the pace is slower.

00:13:08.300 --> 00:13:10.560
So I think that adds to it.

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:12.520
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah,
I think I hear more drones

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:15.990
in the fiddle playing than I
do in most of the other styles.

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:17.890
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Yeah,
and that's the early style.

00:13:17.890 --> 00:13:21.000
They said they played in
Nova Scotia or [inaudible],

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.920
but also there was a Frenchman, I
believe his name was C. C. Robin,

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:27.730
you know, Robin, who came
through and mentioned

00:13:27.730 --> 00:13:30.620
