00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:21.650
In year 2000, there were less
100,000 French-speaking people.

00:16:21.650 --> 00:16:23.470
So that says it right there.

00:16:23.470 --> 00:16:25.520
But it goes through like
different windfalls.

00:16:25.520 --> 00:16:26.820
I mean you got to, like I said,

00:16:26.820 --> 00:16:29.510
on the first television
station, there was French there.

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:31.380
They had an announcer by the
name of Jim Olivia [phonetic],

00:16:31.380 --> 00:16:34.030
who got up every morning
at what 5:30?

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:35.330
&gt;&gt; 5:00 in the morning.

00:16:35.330 --> 00:16:36.630
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet:
And he had groups on.

00:16:36.630 --> 00:16:37.930
Yeah, French royalty.

00:16:37.930 --> 00:16:39.230
He had groups on.

00:16:39.230 --> 00:16:40.530
It was all in French.

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:43.080
And so it was there because
that was the main population.

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:46.210
And then, you know,
Louisiana, because it's been,

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:49.840
basically it's basically
agriculture.

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:52.700
And then when they found oil, then
you have the influence of a lot

00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:55.770
of other people, which
changed the music, etcetera.

00:16:55.770 --> 00:17:00.010
And the transition happened
in the 60s basically.

00:17:00.010 --> 00:17:02.360
I think that the early 60s
you started seeing that.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:05.340
For us, we were like, it
was the young people born

00:17:05.340 --> 00:17:07.500
in the 50s who can remember it.

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:10.410
And then we kind of got
together, it was about 12 of us.

00:17:10.410 --> 00:17:14.380
It when it was like, you know,
Barry Ancelet, because he went

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:16.380
on to become a professor
and a folklorist.

00:17:16.380 --> 00:17:18.670
I mean, there were so many
people, some French people

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:20.960
who were there that helped us out.

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:24.790
The [Inaudible] used to
write in French and English.

00:17:24.790 --> 00:17:26.090
And this was young people.

00:17:26.090 --> 00:17:29.280
And when we were, when
we were young.

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:32.190 position:56%
But that influenced that in a group,
like Dave mentioned, like Coteau

00:17:32.190 --> 00:17:35.200
and BeauSoleil, we weren't
a first young people.

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:38.270 position:56%
I can't even remember people my age.

00:17:38.270 --> 00:17:42.640
I mean I think, oh what's his
name from Kaplan, you know,

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:45.950
Jessie Lashay [phonetic], he
and I are about the same age.

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:47.820
And that's about the
only person my age.

00:17:47.820 --> 00:17:50.300
So it was fully, so you'd
have to go through Marc

00:17:50.300 --> 00:17:54.760
because he was an accordion
player and maker, and Marc Savoy.

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:57.080
And he was, he's 11
years older than I am.

00:17:57.080 --> 00:17:59.840
So he was really at that
point where he saw more

00:17:59.840 --> 00:18:01.960
