00:32:02.230 --> 00:32:04.410
They don't [inaudible] back.

00:32:04.410 --> 00:32:06.960
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So we
haven't talked to Bill much.

00:32:06.960 --> 00:32:09.810
So, you know, a lot of
what we're saying applies

00:32:09.810 --> 00:32:11.110
to percussion as well.

00:32:11.110 --> 00:32:12.420
There's been a lot of
changes over the years,

00:32:12.420 --> 00:32:15.980
and I think that integration
of new sounds,

00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:18.140
and I suppose it must
have changed what you do.

00:32:18.140 --> 00:32:20.050
So talk a little about
that if you would.

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:21.350
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Well sure.

00:32:21.350 --> 00:32:25.090
I mean I was in the, on that
original Swallow Record recording.

00:32:25.090 --> 00:32:28.890
And I had been doing, I hadn't
been playing Cajun music.

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:32.520
I had been doing, with a group
of people, small group of people,

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:35.940
and we improvised music for
choreographers at the university.

00:32:35.940 --> 00:32:41.060
And we would continue going through
this process and codify it so it's

00:32:41.060 --> 00:32:43.130
in its final form for
the performances.

00:32:43.130 --> 00:32:46.800
And I was doing, I was playing
in different size jazz groups

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:51.450
from a quartet to a quintet to
a septet, doing real book stuff.

00:32:51.450 --> 00:32:54.720
And that's what I was
doing when Mike,

00:32:54.720 --> 00:32:58.940
I get word from a mutual
friend of ours, Michael and I,

00:32:58.940 --> 00:33:00.240
Frances [inaudible] the artist.

00:33:00.240 --> 00:33:03.420
I'm an old friend of his.

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:06.660
The word was, Michael was
going to do this record,

00:33:06.660 --> 00:33:08.910
and he wanted to know if
I wanted to participate.

00:33:08.910 --> 00:33:13.680
So I did. So, you know, I
brought some of this to that old,

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:15.270
to the party, so to speak.

00:33:15.270 --> 00:33:19.100
And I was trying to figure out
what to do basically, you know.

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:25.010
And because there was a certain
lightness to a lot of the way

00:33:25.010 --> 00:33:26.310
that these songs were played.

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:29.860
I mean I had heard some English
folk music and things like that.

00:33:29.860 --> 00:33:33.010
So that was part of my thinking
for those songs, you know.

00:33:33.010 --> 00:33:38.040
And I would just apply things where
I thought percussion made sense.

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:41.360
You know, if we need this for
drive or color or whatever,

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:43.490
I would use it there, you know.

00:33:43.490 --> 00:33:45.510
But I didn't just gratuitously
add something.

00:33:45.510 --> 00:33:48.680
And I still don't do that.

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:50.770
But as far as being,
adding percussion

00:33:50.770 --> 00:33:52.510
to Cajun music, nobody does that.

00:33:52.510 --> 00:33:56.030
I'm the only guy, I'm standing
alone out in my field, you know.

00:33:56.030 --> 00:34:00.570
Nobody's come after me, so I
don't know what to make of that.

00:34:00.570 --> 00:34:01.870
But.

00:34:01.870 --> 00:34:03.170
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: It didn't make
any sense to me that you had Billy

00:34:03.170 --> 00:34:05.300
who was so talented,
and played triangle,

00:34:05.300 --> 00:34:06.710
we had to get triangle from.

00:34:06.710 --> 00:34:08.950
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: I didn't even
have one for that recording.

00:34:08.950 --> 00:34:10.250
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Yeah.

00:34:10.250 --> 00:34:12.910
But the thing is, all our
music, we would play, you know,

00:34:12.910 --> 00:34:16.010
exotical music, some
exotic, some creole song.

00:34:16.010 --> 00:34:17.310
Why didn't they use drums?

00:34:17.310 --> 00:34:19.090
That's like the basic thing.

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:20.390
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:34:20.390 --> 00:34:21.690
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: And Billy
had, you know, in his hand,

00:34:21.690 --> 00:34:22.990
and all this kind of stuff.

00:34:22.990 --> 00:34:24.290
And I said, that's good.

00:34:24.290 --> 00:34:25.590
That gels the music.

00:34:25.590 --> 00:34:26.890
That brings it all together.

00:34:26.890 --> 00:34:28.190
It is very unique.

00:34:28.190 --> 00:34:29.900
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Yeah,
and you can change off.

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:33.150
If you have a very kit, you
can change off during a song.

00:34:33.150 --> 00:34:36.980
And it's like, and frankly, I
took that approach from looking

00:34:36.980 --> 00:34:38.930
at early weather report stuff.

00:34:38.930 --> 00:34:42.090
You know, from the beginning
of the 70s, you know.

00:34:42.090 --> 00:34:45.440
And that's, I wasn't quite as
interactive and spontaneous

00:34:45.440 --> 00:34:47.510
in my approach to applying that.

00:34:47.510 --> 00:34:50.340
But still, just the idea that
you could use different things

00:34:50.340 --> 00:34:53.560
in different places to articulate
and whatever, expand upon.

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:56.400
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah, it just
changes the texture during a song.

00:34:56.400 --> 00:34:58.660
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Yeah, yeah, but
that's where I was coming from.

00:34:58.660 --> 00:35:00.890
Frankly, that's where
I still come from.

00:35:00.890 --> 00:35:04.040
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: With that
weather report it's going to rain.

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:05.340
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Not today.

00:35:05.340 --> 00:35:08.760
It looks like, feels like 82,
mostly cloudy at night, you know.

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:10.930
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So did you
even play triangle at first,

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:12.230
or did you have to learn that?

00:35:12.230 --> 00:35:13.530
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: No, I didn't
even own one, you know.

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:16.020
As matter of fact, when we
went to Floyd's Swallow Studio,

00:35:16.020 --> 00:35:17.320
there was one lying around.

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:18.620
They said here, you can use this.

00:35:18.620 --> 00:35:19.920
That was great.

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:21.220
It's a relief.

00:35:21.220 --> 00:35:22.520
I've got something to play here.

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:23.890
And I put, you know, I don't know
if you've heard their record,

00:35:23.890 --> 00:35:25.190
but I put all kinds of stuff on it.

00:35:25.190 --> 00:35:28.880
It's like, well I just brought a
bunch of things, and we had to pile

00:35:28.880 --> 00:35:31.480
in a van as I remember,
David, Michael and I.

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:32.830
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet:
That's pretty much it.

00:35:32.830 --> 00:35:34.130
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: It was
wild, you know.

00:35:34.130 --> 00:35:36.400
At the end of the day, we
would drive up there and work

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:38.060 position:56%
into the night, and then we'd finish

00:35:38.060 --> 00:35:40.030
and then drive back
afterwards, you know.

00:35:40.030 --> 00:35:42.080
I don't even know how
long that took.

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:43.970
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: It
took us a long time.

00:35:43.970 --> 00:35:45.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Yeah, it seemed like.

00:35:45.270 --> 00:35:46.570
It seemed like weeks to me.

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:47.870
You know, so.

00:35:47.870 --> 00:35:49.170
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: With Billy,
you got to see us trying,

00:35:49.170 --> 00:35:51.800
Don Montece [phonetic] is an
accordion player and a bus driver,

00:35:51.800 --> 00:35:54.820
and he's a welder, so
he made these beautiful,

00:35:54.820 --> 00:35:57.000
beautiful triangles from rakes.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:58.300
And you'd have to go to him.

00:35:58.300 --> 00:35:59.600 position:56%
And Billy's got one that's extended.

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:01.170
Don said, I messed up on that one.

00:36:01.170 --> 00:36:02.470
Billy says, I love that one.

00:36:02.470 --> 00:36:05.480
And he played it, what
was it a tractor like,

00:36:05.480 --> 00:36:06.780
some kind of wrench or something.

00:36:06.780 --> 00:36:09.660
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Well the triangle
is, actually Don Montece had made

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:11.980
that for a certain individual,

00:36:11.980 --> 00:36:15.980
a custom [inaudible]
as they say, you know.

00:36:15.980 --> 00:36:17.280
And I saw that.

00:36:17.280 --> 00:36:18.770
And as Michael said,
I want that one.

00:36:18.770 --> 00:36:21.830
He said, well, you know, that
guy, he just recently died,

00:36:21.830 --> 00:36:23.730
so he's not going to be using it.

00:36:23.730 --> 00:36:25.250
So I bought that one from him.

00:36:25.250 --> 00:36:29.290
And the striker, when I was in
college, I was going walking

00:36:29.290 --> 00:36:32.690
into a building in a field, and my
foot hit something, and I looked,

00:36:32.690 --> 00:36:36.720
and it was a gear shift from
apparently like, you know,

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:39.860
like a tractor or something.

00:36:39.860 --> 00:36:41.850
And you see this threading on
the end where the ball went,

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:45.910
with still like the
catalog number on the part.

00:36:45.910 --> 00:36:48.860
But, you know, the thing is,
it's got a great balance.

00:36:48.860 --> 00:36:50.160
&gt;&gt; Yeah, it sounds good.

00:36:50.160 --> 00:36:51.820
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Because it
tapers towards the end.

00:36:51.820 --> 00:36:55.170
And you can do that, and
it balances beautifully.

00:36:55.170 --> 00:36:58.520
And because it's tapered, and
because it's not completely round

00:36:58.520 --> 00:37:01.900
or flat, you can get a lot of
different tonalities out of it.

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:06.360 position:56%
So you get like a capable Cajun
triangle like that or a [inaudible],

00:37:06.360 --> 00:37:09.930
you can use this thing and
apply it in different ways,

00:37:09.930 --> 00:37:14.390
and turning it this way, and you
can get subtle shifts in tonality,

00:37:14.390 --> 00:37:17.110
which can mirror the
melody of the song.

00:37:17.110 --> 00:37:18.410
So.

00:37:18.410 --> 00:37:19.710
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Excellent.

00:37:19.710 --> 00:37:21.010
Well, we got more about
the different tonalities

00:37:21.010 --> 00:37:22.800
of the triangle than the fiddle.

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:26.210
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: The
fiddle just sounds the same.

00:37:26.210 --> 00:37:27.510
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:37:27.510 --> 00:37:29.950
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So I also
wanted to talk to Mitch about some

00:37:29.950 --> 00:37:32.420
of the other groups that you've
been in, like Taso [phonetic]

00:37:32.420 --> 00:37:33.720
and some of those groups.

00:37:33.720 --> 00:37:37.940
What was the philosophy there
with other bands you've been in?

00:37:37.940 --> 00:37:39.950
&gt;&gt; Mitchell Reed: Oh
yeah, with Taso,

00:37:39.950 --> 00:37:43.180
in fact Mike produced our
record, it was to just try

00:37:43.180 --> 00:37:45.500
to sound like the old 78 records.

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:48.740
And we had, we found this guy
in the swam, Philip Alamo,

00:37:48.740 --> 00:37:54.780
he was spraying water lilies
for Wildlife and Fisheries.

00:37:54.780 --> 00:37:57.020
But he sounded just
like these old guys.

00:37:57.020 --> 00:38:01.840
And his accordion even, he played
one of Errol Verret's accordions.

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:06.440
But Mike has like the first
accordion Marc Savoy ever made.

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:09.540
And it's this wild accordion.

00:38:09.540 --> 00:38:13.930
So Mike let us borrow it, and we
did a record, and Mike produced it.

00:38:13.930 --> 00:38:17.530
And it was just really to sound
like those old 78s, you know.

00:38:17.530 --> 00:38:20.110
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: I think
I've got that record.

00:38:20.110 --> 00:38:22.830
&gt;&gt; Mitchell Reed: Oh, okay, yeah.

00:38:22.830 --> 00:38:24.130
Oh good, good.

00:38:24.130 --> 00:38:25.430
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Excellent.

00:38:25.430 --> 00:38:26.730
So good job from all of you.

00:38:26.730 --> 00:38:28.030
&gt;&gt; Mitchell Reed: Thank you.

00:38:28.030 --> 00:38:29.330
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So great.

00:38:29.330 --> 00:38:30.930
And the other person that's now
come up a whole bunch of times

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:33.610
and has also been a
musical partner of yours

00:38:33.610 --> 00:38:35.320
for a long time, is Marc Savoy.

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:38.740
And so talk a little
about the Savoy influence

00:38:38.740 --> 00:38:40.750 position:56%
on Cajun music but also on you guys.

00:38:40.750 --> 00:38:42.050
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet:
You mean the dynasty?

00:38:42.050 --> 00:38:43.790
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah,
the dynasty, the band.

00:38:43.790 --> 00:38:45.090
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well,
the thing about Marc,

00:38:45.090 --> 00:38:47.110
Marc is a super intelligent person,

00:38:47.110 --> 00:38:50.490
which is unusual around
where we live.

00:38:50.490 --> 00:38:52.920
And he's very special.

00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:54.760
Like I said, he was born at
a certain time here he was,

00:38:54.760 --> 00:38:59.310
one foot in one time era, the
other foot in the modern time.

00:38:59.310 --> 00:39:05.050
And he decided, I think he's
celebrating his 50, his 50th year

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:09.380
or something like that,
of opening his door.

00:39:09.380 --> 00:39:13.510
And he did that because, after he
heard that people went in Newport,

00:39:13.510 --> 00:39:15.760
he said oh, it's going
to be popular.

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:19.920
So there was only one or very few
accordion makers at that time.

00:39:19.920 --> 00:39:23.140
So he started making, because
he graduated in engineering.

00:39:23.140 --> 00:39:26.040
And he starting making accordions
because we didn't have that,

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:27.580
I mean they would fall
apart, you know.

00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:31.080
They had these old Hohners or
monarch of Sterlings for sure,

00:39:31.080 --> 00:39:34.480
made pre-World War II Germany.

00:39:34.480 --> 00:39:36.720
And so he started doing that.

00:39:36.720 --> 00:39:39.950
So he was like, he was the
focal point where you find it.

00:39:39.950 --> 00:39:42.780
And if you want to have a
[inaudible] you bring it to him.

00:39:42.780 --> 00:39:44.420
Because it'd bring it to life.

00:39:44.420 --> 00:39:45.720
[Inaudible].

00:39:45.720 --> 00:39:47.800
Marc was just, and it
is, is a treasure trove

00:39:47.800 --> 00:39:49.760
of what was going on at that time.

00:39:49.760 --> 00:39:55.070
It just so happens it was at
that 1976 National Folk Festival

00:39:55.070 --> 00:39:57.060
where Marc just showed up.

00:39:57.060 --> 00:39:58.650
He actually played with us.

00:39:58.650 --> 00:40:01.260
But he would pull me to
the side, come on Mike,

00:40:01.260 --> 00:40:02.560
let's just jam, you know.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:07.310
So we'd go to some, wherever, and
lo and behold this young woman

00:40:07.310 --> 00:40:11.480
by the name of Ann Allen Savoy
from Richmond, Virginia, showed up,

00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:13.730
and like was totally
enamored with the music.

00:40:13.730 --> 00:40:15.500
And she went, and she
and Marc got together.

00:40:15.500 --> 00:40:17.840
And that's Mrs. Savoy.

00:40:17.840 --> 00:40:20.980
And of course, they
had kids all along.

00:40:20.980 --> 00:40:24.090
And their kids have done, I mean
from Sarah, who's in France.

00:40:24.090 --> 00:40:26.000
She's a chef and plays accordion.

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:29.130
To Joel, he was kind
of, music label.

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:32.500
And Wilson who plays boogie
woogie and all this stuff.

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:37.400
And you know, it's like
it's a very solid family.

00:40:37.400 --> 00:40:39.730
But I mean, they're crazy
like everybody else.

00:40:39.730 --> 00:40:41.830
And they just, it's just fun.

00:40:41.830 --> 00:40:45.780
And the thing with this,
Marc is just very aware

00:40:45.780 --> 00:40:47.630
about what is right, what is wrong.

00:40:47.630 --> 00:40:51.810
I mean we've had long discussions
about, you know, in the early days,

00:40:51.810 --> 00:40:56.060
I'm talking about in the early
70s about really the influence

00:40:56.060 --> 00:40:58.610
of the creoles, the black creoles.

00:40:58.610 --> 00:41:03.100
And I was always been a proponent
of Amede Ardoin because, you know,

00:41:03.100 --> 00:41:05.130
because I just love his music.

00:41:05.130 --> 00:41:07.540
And people in Cajun said
oh, he played too many notes

00:41:07.540 --> 00:41:09.170
and choppy and stuff like that.

00:41:09.170 --> 00:41:13.420
But the quality of what he played
and the creativity is just amazing.

00:41:13.420 --> 00:41:16.150
And a lot of us didn't have
access to these things.

00:41:16.150 --> 00:41:21.340
Although Marc, his parents, Amede
played at Marc's parents' house.

00:41:21.340 --> 00:41:24.040
I mean and Dennis used to live
in the house he's living in now.

00:41:24.040 --> 00:41:26.890
So it's a funny thing that happens.

00:41:26.890 --> 00:41:31.010
So he is one of those people
that's just, it's a cornerstone,

00:41:31.010 --> 00:41:32.730
he's a cornerstone of our society.

00:41:32.730 --> 00:41:36.050
And that's just the way it is.

00:41:36.050 --> 00:41:40.160
And he didn't try to be.

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:43.690
He doesn't want any kind of
accolades or anything like that.

00:41:43.690 --> 00:41:46.450
And a lot of people,
oh I can do this.

00:41:46.450 --> 00:41:51.260
And that's another lesson that, you
know, Octa used to say, Octa Clark,

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:55.320
he'd say, well you can't do it
wrong if you do it right, you know.

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:58.220
And I think that's, you just try to
do it right for the right reasons.

00:41:58.220 --> 00:42:00.440
And so Marc has been a
great example of that.

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:02.450
And people sometimes are scared.

00:42:02.450 --> 00:42:04.210
Because if he doesn't like you.

00:42:04.210 --> 00:42:05.510
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:42:05.510 --> 00:42:06.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: I mean,
don't touch that guitar.

00:42:06.810 --> 00:42:08.110
You going to buy it?

00:42:08.110 --> 00:42:09.410
It's time for you to leave.

00:42:09.410 --> 00:42:10.710
You know, he doesn't care.

00:42:10.710 --> 00:42:12.010
I mean he goes beyond
what most, anything.

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:17.150
You know, it's like, he's got
a sign in his shop that says,

00:42:17.150 --> 00:42:19.960
Stradivari made 661 instruments.

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:23.030
The Cajuns have 2,000 of them.

00:42:23.030 --> 00:42:24.510
You know, it's like [inaudible].

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:25.990
And other philosophies.

00:42:25.990 --> 00:42:28.400
So yeah, he's quite an individual.

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:29.700
And the family is great.

00:42:29.700 --> 00:42:33.010
And still, I had dinner with him
last Saturday, so alive and well.

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:34.310
Say hello.

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:35.610
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Alright.

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:37.350
So another thing I wanted
to ask about was songwriter.

00:42:37.350 --> 00:42:40.350
Because you played a couple
of songs today that you wrote.

00:42:40.350 --> 00:42:41.650
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Yeah.

00:42:41.650 --> 00:42:42.950
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
But they, you know,

00:42:42.950 --> 00:42:45.020
they sound like they could be
traditional songs, and certainly,

00:42:45.020 --> 00:42:47.420
they have traditional
expressions in them.

00:42:47.420 --> 00:42:49.950
Just the way that you
wrote them is really

00:42:49.950 --> 00:42:51.610
in keeping with the tradition.

00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:54.370
What's your philosophy on
that, on the songwriting?

00:42:54.370 --> 00:42:57.770
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well, I haven't
written that many songs, you know,

00:42:57.770 --> 00:43:00.300
a hundred or so, but anyway.

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:03.110
You know, it's nice
to do an expression.

00:43:03.110 --> 00:43:04.410
I love traditional music.

00:43:04.410 --> 00:43:05.850
When David and I got
together, that was it.

00:43:05.850 --> 00:43:10.220
I mean we're just going to learn as
much as we can, different styles.

00:43:10.220 --> 00:43:13.980
But there's a certain point, and
I use the metaphor as a wheel.

00:43:13.980 --> 00:43:17.470
Sometimes there's a cog
missing, and you get,

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:20.070
you're not saying exactly
what you want to say.

00:43:20.070 --> 00:43:25.040
So creating a song or writing
a song gives you that element.

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:26.780
And so you perpetuate that.

00:43:26.780 --> 00:43:30.570
And a lot of the songs
that I like to write,

00:43:30.570 --> 00:43:34.290
or did at some points,
was about musicians.

00:43:34.290 --> 00:43:36.620
Like Bebe Carriere or
Freeman Fotno [phonetic],

00:43:36.620 --> 00:43:38.150
people that most people don't know.

00:43:38.150 --> 00:43:41.760
But to us, they're
like, they're revered.

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:43.060
And so songs about that.

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:45.250
Other songs are more modern songs.

00:43:45.250 --> 00:43:47.180
And sometimes they work.

00:43:47.180 --> 00:43:48.480
Sometimes they don't.

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:51.600
And it's wonderful to hear
people play them, you know.

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:54.920
But I don't write them for other
people, I write them for us.

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:57.070
And because it just works
really well with, like I said,

00:43:57.070 --> 00:43:58.680
this key and things like that.

00:43:58.680 --> 00:44:01.830
David sings this song, and
you know, things like that.

00:44:01.830 --> 00:44:03.870
So I enjoy writing.

00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:05.280
I don't write as much anymore.

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:07.650
But I still do, you know.

00:44:07.650 --> 00:44:09.630
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Well on the
other end of that you mentioned,

00:44:09.630 --> 00:44:13.170
there were times when people
didn't have access to some

00:44:13.170 --> 00:44:15.880
of the older music, and they
weren't able to get them either

00:44:15.880 --> 00:44:17.410
because they were on old 78s

00:44:17.410 --> 00:44:19.690
or because they were
old archival recordings.

00:44:19.690 --> 00:44:21.180
And we have an interest
in that because, you know,

00:44:21.180 --> 00:44:22.480
this is the Library of Congress.

00:44:22.480 --> 00:44:23.780
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Oh,
that's where we are?

00:44:23.780 --> 00:44:25.080
I knew it looked familiar.

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:26.380
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
The recordings for.

00:44:26.380 --> 00:44:29.330
So talk about the influence of
archival recording on [inaudible].

00:44:29.330 --> 00:44:31.370
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: I came
here when we got a grant,

00:44:31.370 --> 00:44:35.340 position:56%
it's called the [inaudible]
studies grant at, at that time, USL.

00:44:35.340 --> 00:44:38.440
And it was amazing grant
is that we had music.

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:40.060
We had language.

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:41.860
There's no such thing
as a Cajun dictionary.

00:44:41.860 --> 00:44:45.000
They had been Cajun dictionaries
in the 30s and things like that.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.790
People who studied [inaudible]
amazing stuff that we found.

00:44:47.790 --> 00:44:50.710
Architecture, women,
creole, [inaudible].

00:44:50.710 --> 00:44:55.530
So I was asked to teach
the Cajun or French music.

00:44:55.530 --> 00:44:59.350 position:56%
The name of my course was French
music in Louisiana, opera to zydeco.

00:44:59.350 --> 00:45:01.140
So that' pretty vast.

00:45:01.140 --> 00:45:03.650
One of those things that we
knew about, and I was befriended

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:07.700
in the early 70s, was a woman by
the name of Irene Whitfield Holmes

00:45:07.700 --> 00:45:09.010
who wrote one of the first books.

00:45:09.010 --> 00:45:15.280
It was her 1939 LSU thesis on
folk songs of French Louisiana.

00:45:15.280 --> 00:45:18.370
And you know, another one,
I thought she was dead too.

00:45:18.370 --> 00:45:20.370
My aunt says, no, she lives
right behind over there.

00:45:20.370 --> 00:45:22.780
So I went, and we became
really good friends.

00:45:22.780 --> 00:45:25.740
And she's the one who gave
me my first Amede Ardoin, 78,

00:45:25.740 --> 00:45:27.830
which you could play in those days.

00:45:27.830 --> 00:45:29.520
And she played violin.

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:31.160
So we played these
terrible duets together.

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:33.240
But she, her book, I
learned a lot in the book.

00:45:33.240 --> 00:45:37.240
And some of my first records
where she translated Alan

00:45:37.240 --> 00:45:40.780
and John Lomax's recordings,
transcribed.

00:45:40.780 --> 00:45:44.520
I'd never heard it, and from her
transcriptions we recorded there

00:45:44.520 --> 00:45:45.820
of their songs.

00:45:45.820 --> 00:45:48.060
And then finally in
1979, I came down here

00:45:48.060 --> 00:45:50.790
to collect the whole
Lomax collections,

00:45:50.790 --> 00:45:54.130
and that's when Hickerson was here.

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:56.290
And I just, I couldn't leave.

00:45:56.290 --> 00:45:58.910
I had never heard anything
like this.

00:45:58.910 --> 00:46:00.370
It was so amazing.

00:46:00.370 --> 00:46:02.270
So thanks to the Library of
Congress, and Al, of course.

00:46:02.270 --> 00:46:05.100
We met Alan Lomax when he
came down, blah, blah, blah.

00:46:05.100 --> 00:46:10.660
But yeah, I mean I think it, when
Alec Jabor [phonetic] was here too,

00:46:10.660 --> 00:46:13.340
it kind of, we kind of shy.

00:46:13.340 --> 00:46:16.400
You know, it's like
Washington, but, you know, hmm.

00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:20.240
But once you get here, you realize
it's all run by human beings

00:46:20.240 --> 00:46:21.810
who have the same passion
that we do.

00:46:21.810 --> 00:46:24.010
So it kind of knocked
down those walls.

00:46:24.010 --> 00:46:28.360
So yeah, very much appreciate being
here and being able to perform.

00:46:28.360 --> 00:46:29.660
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick.

00:46:29.660 --> 00:46:31.340
Well we love to have you here, and.

00:46:31.340 --> 00:46:32.640
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well
we're free next week.

00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:34.470
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Alright.

00:46:34.470 --> 00:46:40.080
So yeah, so you know, it's now
time when I'm going to ask you guys

00:46:40.080 --> 00:46:43.840
if there's anything else
you feel that should be said

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:46.170
about your tradition
about Cajun music.

00:46:46.170 --> 00:46:50.300
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: I don't
think it's dying.

00:46:50.300 --> 00:46:51.700
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet:
It's alive and well.

00:46:51.700 --> 00:46:53.000
It's different.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:54.300
It changes.

00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:55.600
It's not the same thing.

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:57.380
Like David was saying, you know,
it's never going to be the same.

00:46:57.380 --> 00:46:58.900
People have to accept that.

00:46:58.900 --> 00:47:03.830 position:56%
Cajun music kind of changes, that's
why it perpetuates itself like that.

00:47:03.830 --> 00:47:06.520
You find more people
singing it in English.

00:47:06.520 --> 00:47:08.170
And that's going to happen.

00:47:08.170 --> 00:47:10.220
Because people can understand it.

00:47:10.220 --> 00:47:11.760
You know, You're not
going to sing a song just

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:13.140
because people can't understand it.

00:47:13.140 --> 00:47:14.440
That's not the point.

00:47:14.440 --> 00:47:16.010
The point of it was
to sing in French

00:47:16.010 --> 00:47:18.150
because that's who
your audience was.

00:47:18.150 --> 00:47:22.390
And you know, it's hard to
deal with this to see a change.

00:47:22.390 --> 00:47:27.650
We saw the changes in the 70s,
you know, when, well first of all,

00:47:27.650 --> 00:47:32.260
when Will and Rodney Balfa
died February 9, 1979.

00:47:32.260 --> 00:47:34.490
That's like the day the music died

00:47:34.490 --> 00:47:37.440
because it was never really
the same, even for Dewey.

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:39.650
And then Nathan died
the year after that.

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:41.280
And Dewey's wife died.

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:46.600
And so anyway, it's
like, you, you know,

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:49.850
you play it because you love it,
and you live life to the fullest.

00:47:49.850 --> 00:47:51.150
And that's what it is.

00:47:51.150 --> 00:47:52.450
And that's still the same.

00:47:52.450 --> 00:47:53.750
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah.

00:47:53.750 --> 00:47:55.050
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: People
only hear stories now.

00:47:55.050 --> 00:47:59.290
That's what I, you know, I play
with a couple of little bands,

00:47:59.290 --> 00:48:04.720 position:56%
and I done one in a town called
Morris, Louisiana, about a month ago

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:06.470
with one of the Pine Leaf Boys.

00:48:06.470 --> 00:48:11.450
And these guys are all, they
all played, but they hired them

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:14.150
to do this Knights
of Columbus thing.

00:48:14.150 --> 00:48:15.490
But what they wanted to hear,

00:48:15.490 --> 00:48:18.240
because I was there, I
knew Canray Fontenot.

00:48:18.240 --> 00:48:20.560
They wanted to hear stories
by Canray they don't know.

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:23.430
They wanted to hear a
couple of stories about,

00:48:23.430 --> 00:48:25.360
even Dewey, but also Dennis.

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:27.720
Nobody knows the story about
Dennis when we took him to New York

00:48:27.720 --> 00:48:29.020
and he almost had a heart attack

00:48:29.020 --> 00:48:30.320
when Michael stole
him out of a hospital.

00:48:30.320 --> 00:48:31.620
And still had his electrodes on.

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:32.920
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Hey Gladys.

00:48:32.920 --> 00:48:34.220
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: But
things like that.

00:48:34.220 --> 00:48:37.740
That's what people, because
they don't, there's no contact.

00:48:37.740 --> 00:48:39.040
Those people aren't there.

00:48:39.040 --> 00:48:40.500
We lived through that.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:42.010
And so we saw this.

00:48:42.010 --> 00:48:45.490
And it's like, you tell the
stories today and people say, no.

00:48:45.490 --> 00:48:46.790
They don't believe any of them.

00:48:46.790 --> 00:48:48.810
Mitchell has stories of
some of the old timers.

00:48:48.810 --> 00:48:51.390
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: But you know,
yeah you got, the time when,

00:48:51.390 --> 00:48:54.240
you know, James Booker
is a great piano player.

00:48:54.240 --> 00:48:56.090
And we were just happen
to be in New Orleans.

00:48:56.090 --> 00:48:58.460 position:56%
So there were about 15 people there.

00:48:58.460 --> 00:49:00.110
And he'd play a song,
and he'd say okay.

00:49:00.110 --> 00:49:01.410
He had a new album.

00:49:01.410 --> 00:49:02.710
Okay, who wants to buy an album?

00:49:02.710 --> 00:49:04.890
Well, after 15 songs,
we all had his album.

00:49:04.890 --> 00:49:06.590
It was his last concert.

00:49:06.590 --> 00:49:07.890
&gt;&gt; He didn't play no more.

00:49:07.890 --> 00:49:10.250
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Fifteen people,
I've talked to about 100 people

00:49:10.250 --> 00:49:11.550
who told me they were there.

00:49:11.550 --> 00:49:12.990
And I said, funny I
don't remember you there.

00:49:12.990 --> 00:49:16.200
And so you have this, even though
it's folklore and people want to.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:17.920
I heard this, anyway.

00:49:17.920 --> 00:49:19.460
So that's changed too.

00:49:19.460 --> 00:49:23.920
So the thing is to set
it straight, you know.

00:49:23.920 --> 00:49:25.220
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winnick: Well
now you have to tell a story

00:49:25.220 --> 00:49:26.520
about Canray, because you.

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:28.870
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: There's
a lot of them.

00:49:28.870 --> 00:49:31.380
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Well,
let me tell you.

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:33.740
[ Overlapped Speaking ]

00:49:33.740 --> 00:49:35.780
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: Michael had
an emergency kidney stone,

00:49:35.780 --> 00:49:38.010
and couldn't make the trip.

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:39.310
[ Inaudible ]

00:49:39.310 --> 00:49:41.430
So it's like, oh, he's
hurting and all this.

00:49:41.430 --> 00:49:42.730
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: So who
you going to get to replace?

00:49:42.730 --> 00:49:44.030
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: Get
Canray to take his place.

00:49:44.030 --> 00:49:45.330
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet:
Like who else, man.

00:49:45.330 --> 00:49:46.630
They said, what?

00:49:46.630 --> 00:49:50.110
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: Yeah so, you
know, Canray, we got him a ticket.

00:49:50.110 --> 00:49:51.410
You know, those were the old days.

00:49:51.410 --> 00:49:53.310
You could change the
name on the ticket.

00:49:53.310 --> 00:49:54.720
And I remember calling up.

00:49:54.720 --> 00:49:57.420
Michael gave me his phone
number, and I talked to his wife.

00:49:57.420 --> 00:49:58.900
She said, he's so excited, David.

00:49:58.900 --> 00:50:00.560
He's drunk in a ditch somewhere.

00:50:00.560 --> 00:50:03.610
I said oh my God, is he
going to show up for the gig?

00:50:03.610 --> 00:50:06.040
We go, I don't even know
if Michael knows this.

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:08.030
He was my roommate.

00:50:08.030 --> 00:50:10.430
And we'll get to that later.

00:50:10.430 --> 00:50:13.100
We play the gig, and you know,
Canray liked to drink a little bit.

00:50:13.100 --> 00:50:17.150
And for some reason the
promoter had a half gallon

00:50:17.150 --> 00:50:19.150
of Early Times backstage.

00:50:19.150 --> 00:50:21.950
And we were playing in
Charlotte, North Carolina.

00:50:21.950 --> 00:50:24.980
And Canray, we all talked about it,
and said alright, we're going to go

00:50:24.980 --> 00:50:26.400
and play two or three
songs, and you come out

00:50:26.400 --> 00:50:27.700
and play the rest of the set.

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:29.110
We'll introduce you and all this.

00:50:29.110 --> 00:50:30.410
No problem.

00:50:30.410 --> 00:50:34.580
We played the three songs, Canray
come, so we play another song.

00:50:34.580 --> 00:50:39.500
Canray. He comes out and
talks for the next 45 minutes.

00:50:39.500 --> 00:50:40.850
Yeah, that reminds
me of another story.

00:50:40.850 --> 00:50:42.150
Another story.

00:50:42.150 --> 00:50:43.450
Okay, so he's a little drunk.

00:50:43.450 --> 00:50:44.750
And we haven't eaten yet.

00:50:44.750 --> 00:50:46.460
So we ended up, the only place
that was open in Charlotte,

00:50:46.460 --> 00:50:50.180
North Carolina, and this is
the truth, was a Hooters.

00:50:50.180 --> 00:50:53.760
And our agent at the time took us,
and we went to eat at a Hooters.

00:50:53.760 --> 00:50:55.680
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: And
of course, it was awful.

00:50:55.680 --> 00:50:57.190
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: But then we
all go to the hotel and it's

00:50:57.190 --> 00:51:01.830
like Canray's my roommate, and I
didn't know he had false teeth.

00:51:01.830 --> 00:51:04.180
And he took out his teeth
and he looked like ET.

00:51:04.180 --> 00:51:07.160
I woke up, who are you?

00:51:07.160 --> 00:51:08.460
Something else, man.

00:51:08.460 --> 00:51:09.960
But he was a character.

00:51:09.960 --> 00:51:12.240 position:56%
These are stories, there's a lot of.

00:51:12.240 --> 00:51:14.290
&gt;&gt; It's the right place
at the right time.

00:51:14.290 --> 00:51:16.590
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: Or the time
we played for Dutch Morial

00:51:16.590 --> 00:51:20.140
who was running for mayor, the
first black mayor of New Orleans.

00:51:20.140 --> 00:51:21.760
And Canray was somehow
involved with this.

00:51:21.760 --> 00:51:24.910
I do not know how, but we
had to play a fundraiser.

00:51:24.910 --> 00:51:26.730
We all get on the stage.

00:51:26.730 --> 00:51:30.530
Well Canray's tuned in between
standard pitch and somewhere.

00:51:30.530 --> 00:51:31.830
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: He's
like [inaudible].

00:51:31.830 --> 00:51:33.130
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: You know, he was
our accordion player in the key

00:51:33.130 --> 00:51:36.700
of C, and Canray is like
in C sharp or above.

00:51:36.700 --> 00:51:38.000
Who knows.

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:42.560
And we play songs in
double keys the whole night.

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:43.860
It was very strong.

00:51:43.860 --> 00:51:46.620
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: That's the way
it's supposed to sound, right.

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:50.070
But Canray was very, I mean he
was born, he lost his father.

00:51:50.070 --> 00:51:51.370
He father was an accordion player,

00:51:51.370 --> 00:51:53.420
just the same caliber
as Amede Ardoin.

00:51:53.420 --> 00:51:55.710
But he chose not to record.

00:51:55.710 --> 00:51:58.950
And he had to work and support his
mother and his sisters, etcetera.

00:51:58.950 --> 00:52:00.250
So he had a hard life.

00:52:00.250 --> 00:52:02.430
You know, he just kind
of had that on it.

00:52:02.430 --> 00:52:05.000
And one of the, I mean there's
so many story like David says.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.740
But one of the times is
when Chris called me up,

00:52:07.740 --> 00:52:11.070
we went to get Canray
just to record him.

00:52:11.070 --> 00:52:13.140
And we had to, and we went
to where he was working.

00:52:13.140 --> 00:52:17.940
He was lifting feed seed, I mean
seed sacks, feed seed sacks.

00:52:17.940 --> 00:52:19.860
Feed seed sacks.

00:52:19.860 --> 00:52:21.160
Yeah, okay.

00:52:21.160 --> 00:52:24.320
Anyway, you know what I mean.

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:26.820
And people who, the
proprietors of the place said,

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:28.540 position:56%
why are you interested in, you know,

00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:31.130
I'm not going to use the
term, but you can imagine.

00:52:31.130 --> 00:52:32.940
And I said, well basically,
he's a genius.

00:52:32.940 --> 00:52:35.290
And they just, you know.

00:52:35.290 --> 00:52:38.540
And we went there that night, and
it was very, we had a great meal.

00:52:38.540 --> 00:52:40.060
And we did the record.

00:52:40.060 --> 00:52:42.630
And he took off his
shoes, and just his foot

00:52:42.630 --> 00:52:44.370
like that against the floor.

00:52:44.370 --> 00:52:48.220 position:56%
So that was one of the high
points, just playing that, he and I.

00:52:48.220 --> 00:52:52.640
But I mean he was, we played
in poor towns in 1980.

00:52:52.640 --> 00:52:54.360
And you know, a lot
of white people there.

00:52:54.360 --> 00:52:57.840
So Canray hits the
bottle again, and he says,

00:52:57.840 --> 00:52:59.940
this is how he opens the concert.

00:52:59.940 --> 00:53:04.890 position:56%
I feel like a fly in a bowl of milk.

00:53:04.890 --> 00:53:07.980
And so, but, you know, it's like.

00:53:07.980 --> 00:53:10.460
That's a whole different
interview, man.

00:53:10.460 --> 00:53:12.380
I'd rather get started like that.

00:53:12.380 --> 00:53:13.680
And you know, everybody knew him.

00:53:13.680 --> 00:53:14.980
Everybody's got their stories.

00:53:14.980 --> 00:53:16.840
&gt;&gt; Billy Ware: Basically,
we were there active

00:53:16.840 --> 00:53:20.620
in this transition point in
which we, what was fundamental

00:53:20.620 --> 00:53:23.430
in the 19th century and the
20th century for that culture.

00:53:23.430 --> 00:53:25.710
You know, and all those
old guys are going away.

00:53:25.710 --> 00:53:27.010
You know.

00:53:27.010 --> 00:53:28.310
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: But
he was amazing to know.

00:53:28.310 --> 00:53:29.610
Several different.

00:53:29.610 --> 00:53:32.070
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: Or the time we
were playing at Carnegie Hall.

00:53:32.070 --> 00:53:33.370
We're all in the cab.

00:53:33.370 --> 00:53:39.100
He gets out of the cab and
says, I've played here before.

00:53:39.100 --> 00:53:40.400
&gt;&gt; I've been here.

00:53:40.400 --> 00:53:42.160
Yeah. I remember that place.

00:53:42.160 --> 00:53:43.460
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: He was a genius.

00:53:43.460 --> 00:53:44.760
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Oh yeah.

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:46.060
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: That's just him.

00:53:46.060 --> 00:53:47.360
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Yeah.

00:53:47.360 --> 00:53:48.860
&gt;&gt; David Doucet: There's
countless others.

00:53:48.860 --> 00:53:50.410
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Well
one thing that, you now,

00:53:50.410 --> 00:53:53.620
this was something you said earlier
reminded me of, you were talking

00:53:53.620 --> 00:53:56.410
about how playing, you know,

00:53:56.410 --> 00:53:58.270
playing English songs
is becoming more common

00:53:58.270 --> 00:54:01.290
because people don't
understand the French songs.

00:54:01.290 --> 00:54:04.050
But that sort of made me
think about the influence

00:54:04.050 --> 00:54:06.130
of other French-speaking places.

00:54:06.130 --> 00:54:08.450
You know, you recorded
your first album in France.

00:54:08.450 --> 00:54:12.270
And Canada is sort
of a big place too.

00:54:12.270 --> 00:54:18.040
So how is that sort of global
French community affected you guys?

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:19.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Michael Doucet: Well, we used to,

00:54:19.340 --> 00:54:21.080
they didn't have a
category for Cajun music.

00:54:21.080 --> 00:54:23.010
We were world music rather.

00:54:23.010 --> 00:54:24.310
They didn't know where to put us.

00:54:24.310 --> 00:54:29.210
It is really world music when you
think about all the influences.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:34.320
You know, it's like what
happened, it wasn't just now.

00:54:34.320 --> 00:54:36.540
It happened in the 50s.

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:39.340
And a certain genre
of music that's mixed

00:54:39.340 --> 00:54:41.730
with rockabilly and
New Orleans music.

00:54:41.730 --> 00:54:43.690
And it's called swamp pop.

00:54:43.690 --> 00:54:47.210
This guy, Broden [phonetic]
came up with that.

00:54:47.210 --> 00:54:48.640
And it's rock and roll.

00:54:48.640 --> 00:54:52.550
And one of the guys, Rod Bernard
saying [inaudible] rock and roll.

00:54:52.550 --> 00:54:55.760
He was actually on
American Bandstand.

00:54:55.760 --> 00:54:59.560
So it's always, you know, we
wanted to make the transition,

00:54:59.560 --> 00:55:00.900
but they wanted to do it

00:55:00.900 --> 00:55:02.450
with electric guitars
and things like that.

00:55:02.450 --> 00:55:04.330
So it wasn't done with accordions.

00:55:04.330 --> 00:55:05.630
That came later.

00:55:05.630 --> 00:55:06.980
And Jimmy C. Newman,
you know he sings

00:55:06.980 --> 00:55:08.570 position:56%
in English too, etcetera, like that.

00:55:08.570 --> 00:55:12.490
So you know, all that,
Kershaw, [inaudible] too.

00:55:12.490 --> 00:55:15.290
I mean it's slowly it's there.

00:55:15.290 --> 00:55:20.160 position:56%
And I think for it to survive, it
has to regenerate to something else.

00:55:20.160 --> 00:55:22.700
As long as it's real, you know.

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:25.200
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Well you
guys definitely play real music.

00:55:25.200 --> 00:55:26.500
I think we can all say that.

